Since you're working on a production codebase and want to impress your lead, I'd recommend avoiding the N+1 query approach. Instead, use one query to find the orphan subscription and one query to delete it. It's cleaner, more scalable, and demonstrates good database optimization.


---

Repository

FedexSubscriptionRepository

@Repository
public interface FedexSubscriptionRepository extends JpaRepository<FedexSubscriptionEntity, UUID> {

    @Query("""
            SELECT fs.subscriptionId
            FROM FedexSubscriptionEntity fs
            WHERE fs.customerId = :customerId
              AND NOT EXISTS (
                    SELECT 1
                    FROM FedexSubscribedAccountEntity fsa
                    WHERE fsa.subscriptionId = fs.subscriptionId
              )
            """)
    Optional<String> findSubscriptionIdWithoutAccounts(@Param("customerId") String customerId);

    @Modifying
    @Transactional
    void deleteBySubscriptionId(String subscriptionId);
}


---

Service Interface

public interface FedexUnsubscriptionService {

    void processFedexUnsubscription(String customerId, String accountNumber);

}

> Although accountNumber is not used in the DB query, keep it in the method signature because it is part of the API request and is useful for logging/auditing.




---

Service Implementation

@Slf4j
@Service
@RequiredArgsConstructor
@Transactional
public class FedexUnsubscriptionServiceImpl implements FedexUnsubscriptionService {

    private final FedexSubscriptionRepository fedexSubscriptionRepository;

    @Override
    public void processFedexUnsubscription(String customerId,
                                           String accountNumber) {

        log.info(new LogBuilder()
                .withMessage("Processing FedEx unsubscription request")
                .withField("customerId", customerId)
                .withField("accountNumber", accountNumber)
                .toString());

        Optional<String> subscriptionId =
                fedexSubscriptionRepository.findSubscriptionIdWithoutAccounts(customerId);

        if (subscriptionId.isEmpty()) {

            log.info(new LogBuilder()
                    .withMessage("No orphan subscription found for customer")
                    .withField("customerId", customerId)
                    .toString());

            return;
        }

        fedexSubscriptionRepository.deleteBySubscriptionId(subscriptionId.get());

        log.info(new LogBuilder()
                .withMessage("Successfully deleted orphan subscription")
                .withField("customerId", customerId)
                .withField("subscriptionId", subscriptionId.get())
                .toString());
    }
}


---

Why this is optimal

Instead of:

Customer
    ↓
Fetch 20 subscriptions
    ↓
Loop 20 times
    ↓
20 count queries
    ↓
Delete

you're doing:

Customer
    ↓
1 query (find orphan subscription)
    ↓
1 delete query

Only 2 database calls, regardless of whether the customer has 2 subscriptions or 200.


---

Unit Tests

You should have these scenarios:

✅ Orphan subscription found → deleteBySubscriptionId() is invoked.

✅ No orphan subscription found → delete is never invoked.

✅ Verify repository methods are called exactly once.



---

One thing to confirm

This implementation assumes there can be at most one subscription without accounts for a customer after an unsubscription event.

If that's a guaranteed business rule, this is the implementation I'd submit. If multiple orphan subscriptions can exist, the repository should return a List<String> instead of an Optional<String>, and the service logic would need to decide which one to delete.